	// 	"text"		: "1\n00:00:04,000 --> 00:00:10,500\nHi! Welcome to Storyline Online, brought\nto you by the Screen Actors Guild Foundation.\n\n2\n00:00:10,500 --> 00:00:16,340\nI'm Molly Ephraim and today we'll be reading Hanukkah in Alaska,\n\n3\n00:00:16,980 --> 00:00:20,460\nby Barbara Brown and Illustrated by Stacey Schuett.\n\n4\n00:00:20,840 --> 00:00:25,680\nI really love reading, but most of all, I like reading to other people,\n\n5\n00:00:25,680 --> 00:00:31,090\npeople younger than me. So maybe if you have\na little brother or a little sister or a little cousin,\n\n6\n00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:36,060\nor even a younger classmate, try reading\nto them. It's really fun.\n\n7\n00:00:38,100 --> 00:00:42,700\nIn Alaska, in winter, we have to watch out for moose.\n\n8\n00:00:42,900 --> 00:00:47,100\nWe have to look both ways when we go out the door, making sure there are no moose around.\n\n9\n00:00:47,400 --> 00:00:51,900\nThat's because moose are very big, and they\nkick things that surprise them or make them angry.\n\n10\n00:00:52,600 --> 00:00:55,300\nTheir big kicks are strong enough to dent a car.\n\n11\n00:00:58,100 --> 00:01:00,760\nMy mother drives slowly in the winter, looking out for moose.\n\n12\n00:01:01,960 --> 00:01:03,880\nWhen my friends and I are playing outside\n\n13\n00:01:03,880 --> 00:01:06,330\nand a moose comes along, we have to hug a tree.\n\n14\n00:01:06,340 --> 00:01:10,260\nA moose can't step on you or knock you over if you're hugging a tree.\n\n15\n00:01:12,340 --> 00:01:18,820\nAlso, during winter in Alaska, it's dark.\nNot just at night for sleeping, but almost all the time.\n\n16\n00:01:19,720 --> 00:01:21,860\nIt doesn't get light until it's already snack time at school,\n\n17\n00:01:21,960 --> 00:01:26,500\nand it's dark again practically\nright after lunch. Daytime is only five hours long.\n\n18\n00:01:26,689 --> 00:01:30,149\nAnd sometimes, when there's so much\nsnow that it covers up the windows,\n\n19\n00:01:30,320 --> 00:01:32,580\ndaylight  can barely peek in.\n\n20\n00:01:37,600 --> 00:01:40,200\nAlaska snow piles up everywhere.\n\n21\n00:01:40,520 --> 00:01:45,340\nIt gets so deep that the moose with their skinny legs have trouble walking in it.\n\n22\n00:01:45,580 --> 00:01:49,020\nThey like to use  people's shoveled driveways and paths.\n\n23\n00:01:49,520 --> 00:01:52,940\nThat's why a moose lives in our backyard.\n\n24\n00:01:53,260 --> 00:01:59,400\nHe wandered up our driveway, found a good spot where he could nibble at our trees, and decided to stay.\n\n25\n00:02:00,360 --> 00:02:03,760\nHe sleeps in our yard and eats our trees.\n\n26\n00:02:03,770 --> 00:02:09,730\nI try throwing carrots to him, even cookies,\nbut he really likes the tree with my blue swing on it.\n\n27\n00:02:11,040 --> 00:02:12,860\nI'm worried about my swing.\n\n28\n00:02:12,870 --> 00:02:18,090\nOnce, we saw a moose walking around town with\na swing in his antlers.\n\n29\n00:02:18,090 --> 00:02:21,160\nHe'd gotten tangled and just tore the whole\nswing away.\n\n30\n00:02:22,960 --> 00:02:28,140\nI think the dark and that moose are making\nme kind of grumpy,\n\n31\n00:02:28,200 --> 00:02:30,960\nbecause even Hanukkah hasn't cheered me up.\n\n32\n00:02:31,060 --> 00:02:33,900\nMy friends and I pretend to be dreidels spinning in the snow,\n\n33\n00:02:33,900 --> 00:02:39,000\nand when the mail lady comes, she always has another present for me from my aunts and uncles Outside.\n\n34\n00:02:39,240 --> 00:02:42,920\n(Do you know that everywhere else from Alaska is called \"Outside\"?)\n\n35\n00:02:45,180 --> 00:02:47,720\nBut every time I light a new candle in our menorah,\n\n36\n00:02:47,760 --> 00:02:53,050\nI look out the window and it's still\ndark, and that moose is still there, too close\n\n37\n00:02:53,050 --> 00:02:58,560\nto my swing and eating our trees.\nMy mother and I throw some apples, hoping\n\n38\n00:02:58,560 --> 00:03:04,180\nhe'll like them instead, but he just watches\nthem fall and eats more tree.\n\n39\n00:03:04,180 --> 00:03:10,140\nOne night as I am lighting the last Hanukkah\ncandle, my father says, \"Let's go outside.\n\n40\n00:03:10,140 --> 00:03:13,909\nI have something to show you.\"\n\"With the moose there?\"\n\n41\n00:03:13,909 --> 00:03:17,189\n\"Don't worry, we'll stay far away.\"\n\n42\n00:03:18,060 --> 00:03:20,840\nI put on my long underwear and two layers of socks.\n\n43\n00:03:21,300 --> 00:03:27,620\nI put on my thick, baggy pants...\n...and a sweatshirt. I put a snowsuit on over all that,\n\n44\n00:03:29,220 --> 00:03:35,240\ntwo layers of mittens, and a hat.\nStill, it's freezing cold outside, and it's very dark,\n\n45\n00:03:35,250 --> 00:03:39,110\nand I do not like being anywhere\nnear that moose.\n\n46\n00:03:39,240 --> 00:03:41,280\nI want that moose away from my swing!\n\n47\n00:03:42,420 --> 00:03:45,600\n\"Dad, what are we waiting for?\"\n\n48\n00:03:45,620 --> 00:03:53,420\n\"Just wait. You'll see.\" But he's looking\nat the sky. I'm looking at that moose.\n\n49\n00:03:54,439 --> 00:03:59,839\nMom says, \"Maybe we can try some fresh spinach.\nMaybe he'll leave your swing alone for something green.\"\n\n50\n00:04:00,620 --> 00:04:04,019\nBut the spinach doesn't work, and I'm freezing.\n\n51\n00:04:04,040 --> 00:04:07,540\nDad says, \"This is a perfect night. You'll see.\"\n\n52\n00:04:08,010 --> 00:04:11,190\nSuddenly, dad points up to the sky.\n\n53\n00:04:11,420 --> 00:04:16,440\nThere are pink and purple and orange ribbons of light!\n\n54\n00:04:16,620 --> 00:04:21,120\nThe sky is full of color, all swirling\nand shining and glowing.\n\n55\n00:04:21,120 --> 00:04:25,160\nAgainst the dark black of the sky, the lights\nare bright and beautiful.\n\n56\n00:04:25,360 --> 00:04:28,120\nI have never seen anything like this.\n\n57\n00:04:28,260 --> 00:04:34,080\nSo much light, and so big. Filling the sky,                coloring the sky.\n\n58\n00:04:34,090 --> 00:04:36,350\nA rainbow on black velvet.\n\n59\n00:04:39,360 --> 00:04:41,639\n\"They're called the northern lights,\" Dad says.\n\n60\n00:04:41,640 --> 00:04:49,540\n\"Aurora borealis. They happen especially up here in Alaska, but only when the sky is just right.\n\n61\n00:04:50,160 --> 00:04:53,300\nOur very own Hanukkah Festival of Lights.\"\n\n62\n00:04:54,460 --> 00:04:56,460\nIt looks like ribbons of wax,\n\n63\n00:04:56,460 --> 00:05:00,620\nall the candles from all the menorahs, melting into the dark, lighting it up.\n\n64\n00:05:01,920 --> 00:05:03,780\nI stare at those lights.\n\n65\n00:05:03,900 --> 00:05:10,220\nI stare so hard, I don't even notice the moose sticking his  head through my swing.\n\n66\n00:05:10,980 --> 00:05:13,500\nNext thing I know, the moose is yanking on the chain,\n\n67\n00:05:13,500 --> 00:05:15,820\npulling on the whole tree.\n\n68\n00:05:15,980 --> 00:05:19,700\nCREAK! CLANK! SNORT! <Audio swinging swing, cracking tree, snorting moose and bellow>\n\n69\n00:05:19,700 --> 00:05:22,550\nI can't stand it. That moose will tear everything up.\n\n70\n00:05:22,560 --> 00:05:30,759\nBut then I have an idea. I run into the house\nand run back outside with my hands full.\n\n71\n00:05:30,759 --> 00:05:35,340\nI wave what I have at the moose, and he sniffs,\nturning his head away from the swing.\n\n72\n00:05:35,340 --> 00:05:41,289\nI back up, laying what I have down in the\nsnow. The moose stretches his head, reaches for it.\n\n73\n00:05:43,020 --> 00:05:46,980\nI keep backing up, laying more down,\nand the moose follows me!\n\n74\n00:05:46,980 --> 00:05:54,200\nOut of the yard, down the driveway, AWAY! I lay the last batch down and race back into our yard.\n\n75\n00:05:56,580 --> 00:06:04,920\nI look at the sky, at the lights. I'm so happy\nto see those lights. I'm so happy that moose is gone.\n\n76\n00:06:05,660 --> 00:06:11,760\nMy parents are surprised. \"What did\nyou feed him?\" they ask. \"What did he like so much?\"\n\n77\n00:06:13,140 --> 00:06:14,919\n\"Latkes,\" I answer.\n\n78\n00:06:18,600 --> 00:06:22,000\nHanukkah can be pretty funny in Alaska,\n\n79\n00:06:24,600 --> 00:06:28,380\nand miracles can happen in a lot of different ways.\n\n80\n00:06:33,140 --> 00:06:35,480\nAnd that's the end.\n\n81\n00:06:35,760 --> 00:06:37,280\nIf you've never had latkes,\n\n82\n00:06:37,289 --> 00:06:41,389\nyou have to try them. They're pancakes, but\nthey're made out of potatoes.\n\n83\n00:06:41,500 --> 00:06:45,860\nBut make sure you have a grown-up to help you out because you have to use very hot oil.\n\n84\n00:06:46,060 --> 00:06:50,420\nMy dad makes them with zucchini, so they are a little healthier. They are really tasty.",
