		"title"		: "How I Learned Geography",
		"text"		: "1\n00:00:03,280 --> 00:00:08,430\nWelcome to Stoyline Online. Brought to you\nby the SAG-AFTRA Foundation.\n\n2\n00:00:08,430 --> 00:00:14,070\nI'm Ed O'Neill and today I'll be reading How\nI Learned Geography written and illustrated\n\n3\n00:00:14,070 --> 00:00:16,630\nby Uri Shulevitz.\n\n4\n00:00:17,360 --> 00:00:19,660\nWhen war devastated the land,\n\n5\n00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:22,180\nbuildings crumbled to dust.\n\n6\n00:00:22,380 --> 00:00:31,260\nEverything we had was lost, and we fled empty-handed. We traveled far, far east to another country,\n\n7\n00:00:31,270 --> 00:00:39,290\nwhere summer were hot and winters were cold,\nto a city of houses made of clay, straw, and camel dung,\n\n8\n00:00:40,100 --> 00:00:44,120\nsurrounded by dusty steppes, burned\nby the sun.\n\n9\n00:00:44,560 --> 00:00:48,200\nWe lived in a small room with a couple we\ndid not know.\n\n10\n00:00:48,210 --> 00:00:50,359\nWe slept on a dirt floor.\n\n11\n00:00:50,359 --> 00:00:54,449\nI had no toys and no books.\n\n12\n00:00:54,449 --> 00:00:58,349\nWorst of all: food was scarce.\n\n13\n00:00:58,780 --> 00:01:04,580\nOne day, Father went to the bazaar to buy\nbread.\n\n14\n00:01:04,589 --> 00:01:08,659\nAs evening approached, he hadn't returned.\n\n15\n00:01:08,659 --> 00:01:10,689\nMother and I were worried and hungry.\n\n16\n00:01:10,689 --> 00:01:13,810\nIt was nearly dark when he came home.\n\n17\n00:01:13,810 --> 00:01:17,430\nHe carried a long roll of paper under his\narm.\n\n18\n00:01:17,430 --> 00:01:21,680\n\"I bought a map,\" he announced triumphantly.\n\n19\n00:01:21,680 --> 00:01:23,579\n\"Where is the bread?\"\n\n20\n00:01:23,579 --> 00:01:24,590\nMother asked.\n\n21\n00:01:24,590 --> 00:01:29,700\n\"I had enough money to buy only a tiny piece\nof bread, and we would still be hungry,\"\n\n22\n00:01:29,700 --> 00:01:30,890\nhe explained apologetically.\n\n23\n00:01:30,890 --> 00:01:34,200\n\"No supper tonight,\" Mother said bitterly.\n\n24\n00:01:34,200 --> 00:01:37,850\n\"We'll have the map instead.\"\n\n25\n00:01:37,850 --> 00:01:39,570\nI was furious.\n\n26\n00:01:39,570 --> 00:01:44,120\nI didn't think I would ever forgive him, and\nI went to bed hungry, while the couple we\n\n27\n00:01:44,120 --> 00:01:47,030\nlived with ate their meager supper.\n\n28\n00:01:47,030 --> 00:01:48,360\nThe husband was a writer.\n\n29\n00:01:48,360 --> 00:01:50,420\nHe write in silence, but, oh!\n\n30\n00:01:50,430 --> 00:01:52,740\nhow loudly he\nchewed.\n\n31\n00:01:52,920 --> 00:01:58,619\nHe chewed a small crust of bread as if it\nwere the most delicious morsel in the world.\n\n32\n00:01:58,619 --> 00:02:02,220\nI envied him his bread and wished I were the\none chew it.\n\n33\n00:02:02,220 --> 00:02:10,300\nI covered my head with my blanket so I would\nnot hear him smacking his lips with such noisy delight.\n\n34\n00:02:10,500 --> 00:02:12,590\nThe next day father hung the map.\n\n35\n00:02:12,590 --> 00:02:15,760\nIt took up an entire wall.\n\n36\n00:02:15,760 --> 00:02:18,160\nOur cheerless room was flooded with color.\n\n37\n00:02:18,160 --> 00:02:24,010\nI became fascinated by the map and spent long\nhours looking at it, studying its every detail,\n\n38\n00:02:24,010 --> 00:02:28,290\nand many days drawing it on any scrap of paper\nthat chanced my way.\n\n39\n00:02:28,290 --> 00:02:33,770\nI found strange-sounding names on the map\nand savored their exotic sounds,\n\n40\n00:02:33,980 --> 00:02:42,659\nmaking a little rhyme out of them: Fukuoka Takaoka\nomsk, Fukuyama Nagayama Tomsk, Okazaki Miyazaki\n\n41\n00:02:42,659 --> 00:02:46,060\nPinks, Pennsylvania Transylvania Minsk!\n\n42\n00:02:46,060 --> 00:02:51,660\nI repeated this rhyme like a magic incantation\nand was transported far away\n\n43\n00:02:51,840 --> 00:02:53,560\nwithout ever leaving our room.\n\n44\n00:02:53,569 --> 00:02:56,360\nI landed in burning deserts.\n\n45\n00:02:56,360 --> 00:03:00,349\nI ran on beaches and felt their sand between\nmy toes.\n\n46\n00:03:00,349 --> 00:03:05,650\nI Climbed snowy mountains where icy winds\nlicked my face.\n\n47\n00:03:05,650 --> 00:03:10,810\nI saw wondrous temples where stone carving\ndanced on the walls,\n\n48\n00:03:10,920 --> 00:03:14,159\nand birds of all colors sang on the rooftops.\n\n49\n00:03:14,159 --> 00:03:19,690\nI pass through fruit groves eating as many\npapayas and mangos as I pleased.\n\n50\n00:03:19,690 --> 00:03:25,050\nI drank fresh water and rested in the shade\nof palm trees.\n\n51\n00:03:25,050 --> 00:03:32,490\nI cam to a city of tall buildings and counted\nzillions of windows, falling asleep before I could finish.\n\n52\n00:03:32,659 --> 00:03:40,190\nAnd so I spent enchanted hours far, far from\nour hunger and misery.\n\n53\n00:03:40,190 --> 00:03:42,680\nI forgave my father.\n\n54\n00:03:42,680 --> 00:03:44,720\nHe was right, after all.\n\n55\n00:03:45,640 --> 00:03:50,760\nYou know, I like this story because it took\nthe boy out of his desprate situation to other\n\n56\n00:03:50,769 --> 00:03:53,720\nworlds that he enjoyed so much more.\n\n57\n00:03:53,720 --> 00:03:59,019\nIt reminds me of when I was a boy of twelve.\n\n58\n00:03:59,019 --> 00:04:05,980\nI discovered an author by the name of Mark\nTwain and the name of the book was Huckleberry\n\n59\n00:04:05,980 --> 00:04:12,570\nFinn and it took me down the Mississippi River\nand lots of adventures that I wouldn't normally\n\n60\n00:04:12,570 --> 00:04:16,110\nhave had in Youngstown Ohio.\n\n61\n00:04:16,320 --> 00:04:17,880\nReading can do that for you.\n\n62\n00:04:18,420 --> 00:04:19,980\nIt can take you to other worlds, other places,\n\n63\n00:04:19,980 --> 00:04:23,500\nother experiences that you would never normally have.\n\n64\n00:04:23,500 --> 00:04:28,550\nThank you for watching Storyline Online and\ndon't forget to check out all of our stories.\n\n65\n00:04:28,550 --> 00:04:31,450\nKeep watching. And keep reading.",
